This is the code archive for https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.12893

Briefly, this is to parameterize interaction potentials by Reinforcement Learning via OpenAI Stable-Baselines3.

# 1. How to run the code

0). Install PyTorch, Stable-Baselines3, and LAMMPS;
1). Clone the code, copy it under a parent folder called "coarse_grained_cellulose_coefficients_code";
2). Set environmental variable "CLL_CG_HOME" to the parent folder of "coarse_grained_cellulose_coefficients_code";
3). Copy the "eipifun_env_pool" and configure envs as shown in the "supplementary";
4). Run initial_training.py and following_training.py as the job scripts shown in the "supplementary".

# 2. What are the versions for eipifun_env_pool and physics_computation_pool

For version vXY, X means mapping and potential configuration and Y means bonded or nonbonded.

For X, 2,3,5, are three different mappings, and 4 is a derivative of 3 trying to address second summit with double well potentials.
For Y, 1,2 are bonded only, 3,4 are nonbonded only with determined bonded coefficients, 5 are coupled. 2 shares the same physics computation code as 1, while 4,5 share the same physics computation code as 3. Higher version number for Y means simplified envs with narrower range.

The env versions used in the manuscript is v32 (bonded) and v34 (nonbonded).

In the eipifun_env_pool, there is a special "temp_envs" folder; they are simplified envs with less independent variables and narrower range. The four important temp_envs are ended with suffix a,b,c,d.
The documented the simplified process during the development. a is the narrowest one, d is narrowed based on normal v34.

Because vX1 and vX3 are only preserved for reference, when debugging and running parallel training, fake vX1 and vX3 can be created.

All the trials are preserved for anyone interested in.

# Rough but useful tools

In the "physics_computation_pool/configure", you can copy and create variant versions. The most important one is "turn_off_threshold.sh"; it will generate the "without thresholds" variant for parallel training.

In the "physics_computation_pool/test_only", all the 100 random seeds for 100 replica simulations are documented in "modify_random_seed.sh". You can run the same replica simulation using "replica_test.sh".


